04592nam a22007815i 9781442688513DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426885137 a10.3138/97814426885132doi  a(DE-B1597)465357  a(OCoLC)1013936684  a(OCoLC)944176667  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB995.L654 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a1911 aWalmsley, Gerard, eauthor.10aLonergan on Philosophic Pluralism :bThe Polymorphism of Conciousness as the Key to Philosophy /cGerard Walmsley. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Contextualizing the Inquiry into Polymorphic Consciousness and Philosophical Pluralism -- t1. Aims/Relevance/Procedure -- t2. Grounding Polymorphism: Polymorphism and the Structure of Human Being -- t3. Polymorphism in Insight: Patterns of Experience -- t4. Further Patterns of Experience? -- t5. Polymorphism: The One and Only Key to Philosophy? -- t6. Polymorphism in Method in Theology -- tConcluding Remarks: Towards a Lonerganian Metaphilosophy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his influential philosophical work Insight, Bernard Lonergan made the intriguing and problematic claim that "the polymorphism of consciousness is the one and only key to philosophy." In Lonergan on Philosophical Pluralism, Gerard Walmsley examines Lonergan's many discussions of the different forms of human consciousness, as well as his sustained responses to the problems raised by philosophical and cultural pluralism. Looking closely at Lonergan's thoughts on patterns of experience, different levels of consciousness, and the differentiations of consciousness that occur through the historical development of individual human minds, Walmsley shows how polymorphic consciousness allows individuals to understand a range of philosophical positions. By understanding this range, an individual is able to sympathetically and critically appreciate different positions. Testing the strength of Lonergan's position, he directly engages postmodern thought and comparative philosophy to demonstrate that Lonergan's account of polymorphic consciousness provides a better basis for a positive evaluation of difference than does the work of many postmodern thinkers. An ambitious and soundly argued work, Lonergan on Philosophical Pluralism is both an illuminating study of Lonergan's thought, and an intriguing proposal for how difference and pluralism can be understood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aConsciousness. 0aDifference (Philosophy) 0aDifference (Philosophy). 0aPluralism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442688513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442688513.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG